node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNA on May 18, 2020. Image may contain: 1 person, text that says 'TeleRad NASA LINYA This Filipino reporter kept calm while her pet cats fought on live national television'

node.text: @hillazaro Sino ba kasi yung Eggward na yun HAHAHAHAHA

There was a battle of epic proportions going on in the background, but Filipino reporter Doris Bigornia was committed to doing her job on live national television.

The amusing video of a catfight between Bigornia’s two cats – Bella and Nala – which happened right behind her, took place last week. And admirably, she continued reporting, with only the occasional side-glance at her naughty pets. She shared the clip of the incident on her Twitter page, writing: “Children!!! There is a law in the studio!” The video clip has gone viral with more than two million views.

Room Rater, a Twitter account that rates Skype rooms and Zoom rooms, joked in a tweet: “The room is an 8. The cat fight is 10/10.” Meanwhile, another user wrote: “The cat fight was more entertaining than “Cats” the movie. Cat fight: 10/10. “Cats” the movie: 0/10.” Read more on CNA Lifestyle, link in bio. #catfight #catsofInstagram #cats #Philippines #television (Photo: Twitter/Doris Bigornia)

@likeparaparaparadise you are over-reacting 🤦‍♂️, no matter what we do, everyone of us are unique, with our own set of mindset, behaviour, beliefs and values. Biologically when we see others, we automatically judge but we resist, tolerate and appreciate. If you want to stop segregation you have to annihilate the very thing that causes it, which is diversity. Diversity is conflicting, but at the same time beautiful at the very essence of conflict yet harmony. Rather than closing an eye or reprimanding the showcase of diversity, it's better to appreciate. Hence, not put the identity in news will make the news less informative unneccesarily, especially if it's an innocent and good news like this one.

@likeparaparaparadise if the news is harming for a particular identity, and yes I agree, you shouldn't associate the identity with the news because people may take the meaning in social media to different extents, sometimes even radicalising it against the innocent.

Just a question. Why do you have to emphasis that she’s Philipino? Does that affect how good of a reporter she is? Honestly this is why we have segregation etc in the world. We label people based on their ethnicity/race etc, instead of just seeing them as people. Would the segment have been any different if she had been Thai,  Malay, or even Caucasian? I hardly think so....
